00:49:02.910 --> 00:49:04.750
people stayed because it was their home?

00:49:04.750 --> 00:49:09.060
I mean, my house is here, my business is here,
my people are here, my familyís here, why

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:10.060
would I move?

00:49:10.060 --> 00:49:13.600
Why would I go away?

00:49:13.600 --> 00:49:18.430
Sort of motivating them to stay and not understanding
downstream the consequences of anything that

00:49:18.430 --> 00:49:21.660
might happen out of that, can you say a little
bit more about that?

00:49:21.660 --> 00:49:22.690
&gt;&gt;Edith Sheffer: Yeah, absolutely.

00:49:22.690 --> 00:49:27.170
And this, I think, speaks to the exact point;
nobody knew what was gonna happen.

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:31.170
And, so, when you talk, I assume youíre talking
about East Germans who stayed in Sonneberg

00:49:31.170 --> 00:49:33.020
and didnít go to the West.

00:49:33.020 --> 00:49:38.010
Yeah, they would have a business, they would
have parents they were taking care of, they

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:42.040
would have a whole life, a whole community
where they were living and it wasnít clear

00:49:42.040 --> 00:49:43.250
what was gonna happen.

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:49.619
Many thought that this barrier was ridiculous
and it would be temporary and no one could

00:49:49.619 --> 00:49:52.540
imagine it could actually be permanent.

00:49:52.540 --> 00:49:58.890
Then, ironically, as the border became stronger
and stronger it got harder to leave because

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:01.250
it implicated your relatives if you left.

00:50:01.250 --> 00:50:05.280
They would pay the consequences in not being
able to attend universities or follow the

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:07.240
career of their choice.

00:50:07.240 --> 00:50:13.140
So there were a lot of reasons that people
wound up staying and it was absolutely a very

00:50:13.140 --> 00:50:14.230
complicated calculation.

00:50:14.230 --> 00:50:20.540
And, as you said, in this early period it
was hard to know what was gonna happen.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:27.869
&gt;&gt;male #1: I have a, first question, did the
formation of the wall and separation of the

00:50:27.869 --> 00:50:32.270
society change East Germany and West Germany
in ways other than the political system?

00:50:32.270 --> 00:50:38.920
I had a German professor who said the language
was changing and what happened culturally

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:41.420
between the two halves because of the separation?

00:50:41.420 --> 00:50:45.260
&gt;&gt;Edith Sheffer: Yeah and exactly as you say
itís amazing to me two different cultures

00:50:45.260 --> 00:50:48.880
formed out of one formerly similar region.

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:51.530
And this happened in a variety of ways.

00:50:51.530 --> 00:50:56.000
Germans talk about this famous wall in the
head, you may have heard about this, and people

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:00.040
say it still exists between East and West
Germans, thereís this wall in the head which

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:02.930
is not only a cultural divide but a mental
divide.

00:51:02.930 --> 00:51:08.430
Some people believe East and West Germans
